    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, it is very common for fiddle leaf fig roots to look messy and tangled when the plant outgrows its pot, but handling them correctly is key to a smooth repotting. Gently tease the root ball apart with your fingers or a small trowel to separate the roots, being careful not to snap the thick, fibrous roots, and only prune any that are actually dead or excessively long. You should also check for dark or discolored roots, as these can indicate root rot or a lack of oxygen, but if the roots feel firm and slightly dark, they are often just a sign that the plant is healthy and ready for a fresh environment.",
